EXCURSUS V.

THE GENERAL NATURE OF OBLIGATIONS.

Tris term obligatio properly indicates a legal relation between two definite persons, whereby the one (creditor, Dig. 50. 16. rr, and ra. pr.) is entitled to a certain actor forbearance on the part oi the other (debitor). The contrast between it and the relation existing in the case oi ownership, possession, or other legal rights, is well marked by Paulus in Dig. 44. 7. 3. pr. ‘obligationum substantia non in eo consistit, ut aliquod corpus nostrum, aut servitutem nostram faciat, sed ut aliurn nobis obstringat ad dandum aliquid, vel laciendum, vel praestandum,’ with which may be compared Blr. iv. 6. r ins. ‘namque agit unus quisque aut cum eo, qui ei obligatus est . ..quo casu proditae sunt actiones in personam . . . aut cum eo agit qui nullo iure ei obligatus est, movet tamen alicui de aliqua re controversiam, quo casu proditae actiones in rem sunt.’ No better explanation oi this contrast can be found than Austin’s exposition of the difference between rights in rem and rights in personam, the meritos which, however, is marred by his use of the term obligation to denote the duty corresponding to rights of the former as well as oi the latter class

But though this is the proper and normal meaning oi the term, obligatio is sometimes used in other senses, and more especially to express one or other limb oi the relation in contradistinction to the other ; thus, it signifies the right of the creditor only in the common phrase adquirere obligationem (Bk. iii. 28, Dig.45. 1. 126. ²3 ag. 3. 46: cs. Bk. iia. a supa), and the duty of the debitor only in Dig. ra. r. 36; 46. 1. 5. ar, ib. 3. 95. g, as wellas in the definition given in Bk. iii. 13. pr. supr. Sometimes it denotes specifically the act or event from which the relation arises, as in Cod. 11. 47. 22, Dig. a. 14. r. 3, as well as in the expressions verborum obligatio, litteramm obligatio, etc. hgain, though onlya person can properly be ‘obli- gatus’ objects which are pledged are occasionally spoken of by analogy as subject to an obligation, e. g. Blr. iii. 27. a supr, Dig. 20.
